RT:Amorebieta, Fernando}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Anzo\u00e1tegui]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan people of Basque descent]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan emigrants to Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan footballers]]\n[[Category:Basque footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:CD Basconia footballers]]\n[[Category:Bilbao Athletic footballers]]\n[[Category:Athletic Bilbao footballers]]\n[[Category:Sporting de Gij\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Fulham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Middlesbrough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Club Atl\u00e9tico Independiente footballers]]\n[[Category:Paraguayan Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Cerro Porte\u00f1o players]]\n[[Category:Spain youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Venezuela international footballers]]\n[[Category:2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:Basque Country international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Argentina]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Paraguay]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Argentina]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Paraguay]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan expatriate sportspeople in Argentina]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan expatriate sportspeople in Paraguay]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Spanish name|Amorebieta|Mardaras}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Fernando Amorebieta\n| image = Fernando_Amorebieta.png\n| caption = Amorebieta in action for [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] in 2014.\n| fullname = Fernando Gabriel Amorebieta Mardaras<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/news/news/2013-14/aug/premier-league-squad-numbers-seasons-2013-14.html|title=Barclays Premier League squad numbers 2013/14|publisher=Premier League|date=16 August 2013|accessdate=17 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130925003258/http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/news/news/2013-14/aug/premier-league-squad-numbers-seasons-2013-14.html|archivedate=25 September 2013|df=dmy}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|3|29|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Pedro Mar\u00eda Freites Municipality|Cantaura]], Venezuela\n| height = {{convert|1.92|m|abbr=on}}\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]]\n| currentclub = [[Cerro Porte\u00f1o]]\n| clubnumber = 5\n| youthyears1 = 1995\u20131996 | youthclubs1 = Colegio San Miguel\n| youthyears2 = 1996\u20132003 | youthclubs2 = [[Athletic Bilbao cantera|Athletic Bilbao]]\n| years1 = 2003\u20132004 | clubs1 = [[CD Basconia|Basconia]] | caps1 = 26 | goals1 = 1\n| years2 = 2004\u20132005 | clubs2 = [[Bilbao Athletic]] | caps2 = 35 | goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2005\u20132013 | clubs3 = [[Athletic Bilbao]] | caps3 = 195 | goals3 = 3\n| years4 = 2013\u20132016 | clubs4 = [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] | caps4 = 44 | goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 2015 | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] (loan) | caps5 = 6 | goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2015\u20132016 | clubs6 = \u2192 [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] (loan) | caps6 = 13 | goals6 = 0<!--THESE LOANS ARE ENTIRELY SEPARATE, DO NOT MERGE-->\n| years7 = 2016\u20132017 | clubs7 = [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n|Sporting Gij\u00f3n]] | caps7 = 27 | goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2017\u20132018 | clubs8 = [[Club Atl\u00e9tico Independiente|Independiente]] | caps8 = 11 | goals8 = 0\n| years9 = 2019\u2013 | clubs9 = [[Cerro Porte\u00f1o]] | caps9 = 5 | goals9 = 0\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = 2004 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain U19]] | nationalcaps1 = 4 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2007\u2013 | nationalteam2 = [[Basque Country national football team|Basque Country]] | nationalcaps2 = 4 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2011\u20132015 | nationalteam3 = [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]] | nationalcaps3 = 15 | nationalgoals3 = 1\n| club-update = 14:30, 06 March 2020 (UTC).\n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n\n'''Fernando Gabriel Amorebieta Mardaras''' (born 29 March 1985) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for Paraguayan club [[Cerro Porte\u00f1o]] as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]].\n\nHe spent most of his career with [[Athletic Bilbao]], appearing in 253 competitive matches over eight [[La Liga]] seasons and scoring four goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lavinotinto.com/03-11-2011/amorebieta-cumplio-su-partido-200-con-el-athletic/|title=Amorebieta cumpli\u00f3 su partido 200 con el Athletic|trans-title=Amorebieta played 200th match with Athletic|publisher=La Vinotinto|language=Spanish|date=3 November 2011|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/1821640/0/fernando-amorebieta/defensa-athletic/fichaje-fulham-premier-league/|title=El Fulham confirma el fichaje del defensa Fernando Amorebieta por cuatro temporadas|trans-title=Fulham confirm signing of defender Fernando Amorebieta for four seasons|newspaper=[[20 minutos]]|language=Spanish|date=22 May 2013|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> He also competed professionally in England (with [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] and [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]), Argentina and Paraguay.\n\nInternationally, Amorebieta played for [[Spain national youth football team|Spain]] as a youth, but later decided to represent [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]] at senior level, appearing for the nation at the [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Athletic Bilbao===\nBorn in [[Pedro Mar\u00eda Freites Municipality|Cantaura]], [[Anzo\u00e1tegui]], [[Venezuela]], Amorebieta joined [[Athletic Bilbao]] in 1996, aged 11. He met the club's [[Athletic Bilbao signing policy|eligibility standards]] having been raised in the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque]] town of [[Iurreta]] and through his parents, both of whom hailed from the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mundo/noticias/2012/05/120508_athletic_bilbao_fain_binda_cch.shtml|title=\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 en el Athletic de Bilbao solo juegan vascos?|trans-title=Why do Athletic Bilbao play with Basques only?|publisher=[[BBC Mundo]]|last=Fain Binda|first=Ra\u00fal|language=Spanish|date=9 May 2012|accessdate=8 July 2012}}</ref> After progressing through the ranks \u2013 alongside [[Fernando Llorente]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://athletic.elcorreo.com/noticias/2012-03-01/amistoso-entre-llorente-amorebieta-20120301.html|title=Amistoso entre Llorente y Amorebieta|trans-title=Friendly between Llorente and Amorebieta|newspaper=[[El Correo]]|last=G\u00f3mez Pe\u00f1a|first=J.|language=Spanish|date=1 March 2012|accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref>\u2013 including [[CD Basconia]] (the [[farm team]]) and [[Bilbao Athletic]] (the [[reserve team|reserves]]), he made his first-team debut in [[2005\u201306 La Liga|2005\u201306]], becoming an undisputed first-choice in the subsequent [[La Liga]] seasons.\n\nAmorebieta played in a total of 47 official matches in [[2009\u201310 La Liga|2009\u201310]], helping Athletic reach the [[Single-elimination tournament|round-of-32]] in [[2009\u201310 UEFA Europa League|the campaign]]'s [[UEFA Europa League]] as well as an eighth-place finish in the league; he collected 18 [[Penalty card#Yellow card|yellow cards]] in the process, being [[Ejection (sports)|sent off]] twice.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2011/11/12/futbol/equipos/athletic/1321095019.html|title=Amorebieta se vuelve 'loco' con los grandes|trans-title=Amorebieta goes 'crazy' with big clubs|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|last=Mart\u00ednez|first=Endika|language=Spanish|date=12 November 2011|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nAmorebieta began [[2012\u201313 La Liga|2012\u201313]] nursing a [[Athletic pubalgia|pubalgia]] ailment,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europapress.es/deportes/futbol-00162/noticia-futbol-amorebieta-athletic-cuatros-semanas-baja-ser-operado-exito-molestias-pubalgia-20120720143901.html|title=F\u00fatbol.\u2013 Amorebieta (Athletic), cuatros semanas de baja tras ser operado con \u00e9xito de sus molestias de pubalgia|trans-title=Football.\u2013 Amorebieta (Athletic), four weeks out after successful pubalgia surgery|publisher=[[Europa Press (news agency)|Europa Press]]|language=Spanish|date=20 July 2012|accessdate=9 May 2013}}</ref> and was later involved in a dispute over the extension of his contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deia.com/2012/12/19/athletic/amorebieta-lo-tomas-o-lo-dejas|title=Amorebieta: lo tomas o lo dejas|trans-title=Amorebieta: take it or leave it|newspaper=[[Deia (newspaper)|Deia]]|last=Artetxe|first=Jos\u00e9 L.|language=Spanish|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=9 May 2013|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130629002403/http://www.deia.com/2012/12/19/athletic/amorebieta-lo-tomas-o-lo-dejas|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2013/01/30/paisvasco/1359547206.html|title=Urrutia: 'Ya no hay oferta por Amorebieta'|trans-title=Urrutia: 'We no longer have an offer for Amorebieta'|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|last=Rodr\u00edguez Vi\u00f1as|first=Sergio|language=Spanish|date=30 January 2013|accessdate=9 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Fulham===\nOn 15 April 2013, Amorebieta agreed to sign a four-year deal with [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on a [[Free transfer (association football)|free transfer]] effective as of 1 July, after the expiration of his link with Athletic Bilbao.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2309345/Fernando-Amorebieta-agrees-sign-Fulham.html|title=Former Arsenal target Amorebieta agrees to sign for Fulham on free transfer|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|accessdate=15 April 2013|location=London|last=Kay|first=Alex|date=15 April 2013}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=November 2019}} The [[Premier League]] club officially announced his signing on 22 May,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2013/may/22/amorebieta-signs|title=Amorebieta arrives|publisher=Fulham F.C|date=22 May 2013|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> and he made his debut on 14 September, coming on as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Kieran Richardson]] in a 1\u20131 draw against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] at [[Craven Cottage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23999576|title=Fulham 1\u20131 West Brom|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|last=Abraham|first=Tim|date=14 September 2013|accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nAmorebieta was sent off on 22 March 2014, for conceding a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] with a foul on [[David Silva]] in an eventual 0\u20135 defeat at [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/287591/report|title=Premier League: Manchester City thrash Fulham 5\u20130 as Yaya Toure nets hat-trick|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=22 March 2014|accessdate=11 May 2015}}</ref> He scored his first goal in [[Football in England|English football]] on 26 April, netting his team's second in an eventual 2\u20132 home draw with [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/27084885|title=Fulham 2\u20132 Hull City|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Oliver|first=Pete|date=26 April 2014|accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref> he made 26 appearances overall in [[2013\u201314 Premier League|his debut season]], which ended with relegation.<ref name=Boro>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32050673|title=Middlesbrough sign Amorebieta as Husband joins Fulham|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 March 2015|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March 2015, after returning from three months out injured,<ref name=Boro/> Amorebieta was sent off in Fulham's 1\u20135 home defeat by [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] for bringing down [[Callum Wilson (English footballer)|Callum Wilson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31654572|title=Fulham 1\u20135 AFC Bournemouth|publisher=BBC Sport|date=6 March 2015|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> On the 25th, he was loaned to fellow [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] until the end of [[2014\u201315 Football League Championship|the campaign]], with left-back [[James Husband (footballer)|James Husband]] moving in the opposite direction.<ref name=Boro/> He scored his first goal for the club on 8 May, coming on as a 73rd-minute substitute for [[Lee Tomlin]] and netting a last-minute winner for a 2\u20131 away win over [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] in the [[2015 Football League play-offs|play-off semi-finals]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32566915|title=Brentford 1\u20132 Middlesbrough|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Stevens|first=Rob|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> he was unused in [[2015 Football League Championship play-off Final|the final]] at [[Wembley Stadium]], a 0\u20132 defeat to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32776552|title=Middlesbrough 0\u20132 Norwich|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Shepka|first=Phil|date=25 May 2015|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 August 2015, Amorebieta returned to the [[Riverside Stadium]] for the entirety of [[2015\u201316 Football League Championship|the season]], with Husband again being lent to Fulham for a month as part of the deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34090682|title=Fernando Amorebieta: Fulham defender joins Middlesbrough|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 August 2015|accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref> On 1 February of the following year, however, he was recalled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/news/article/2016/middlesbrough-fernando-amorebieta-2933325.aspx|title=Fernando Amorebieta leaves Boro and returns to Fulham|publisher=Middlesbrough F.C|date=1 February 2016|accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Sporting Gij\u00f3n===\nOn 22 July 2016, Amorebieta returned to Spain and its top division after agreeing to a three-year contract at [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realsporting.com/webrsg/index.php/template/actualidad/6957-amorebieta-es-ya-sportinguista|title=Amorebieta es ya jugador del Sporting|trans-title=Amorebieta is already a Sporting player|publisher=Sporting Gij\u00f3n|language=Spanish|date=22 July 2016|accessdate=23 July 2016}}</ref> He made his debut on 21 August, playing the full 90 minutes in a 2\u20131 home win against former club Athletic.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2016/08/21/primera/1471777203_869286.html|title=El Sporting despacha a un Athletic atolondrado|trans-title=Sporting get rid of dazed Athletic|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|last=Cuenca|first=Nika|language=Spanish|date=21 August 2016|accessdate=22 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Later years===\nOn 10 July 2017, following [[2016\u201317 La Liga|Sporting's relegation]], Amorebieta moved to Argentina and joined [[Club Atl\u00e9tico Independiente]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sporting.elcomercio.es/amorebieta-jugador-independiente-20170710113236-nt.html|title=Amorebieta ya es jugador del Independiente de Avellaneda|trans-title=Amorebieta is already an Independiente de Avellaneda player|newspaper=[[El Comercio (Spain)|El Comercio]]|language=Spanish|date=10 July 2017|accessdate=10 July 2017}}</ref> In January 2019, the [[free agent]] agreed to a two-year deal at [[Cerro Porte\u00f1o]] of the [[Paraguayan Primera Divisi\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldesmarque.com/bizkaia/athletic-club/192469-amorebieta-ficha-por-el-cerro-porteno-paraguayo|title=Amorebieta ficha por el Cerro Porte\u00f1o paraguayo|trans-title=Amorebieta signs for Paraguay's Cerro Porte\u00f1o|publisher=El Desmarque|language=Spanish|date=12 January 2019|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Spain===\nAmorebieta was part of the [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spanish under-19]] squad that won the [[UEFA European Under-19 Championship|UEFA European Championship]] in [[2004 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2004]].<ref name=\"ATHLETIC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.athletic-club.net/web/main.asp?a=1&b=1&c=1&d=1&jokalaria=557&idi=2|title=Amorebieta|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|accessdate=2 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120918084014/http://www.athletic-club.net/web/main.asp?a=1&b=1&c=1&d=1&jokalaria=557&idi=2|archive-date=18 September 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> In August 2008, he was called up by new [[Spain national football team|senior team]] manager [[Vicente del Bosque]] for a [[Exhibition game|friendly]] against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archivo.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/seleccion/es/desarrollo/1155600.html|title=Amorebieta e Iraola, sorpresas en la lista de Del Bosque|trans-title=Amorebieta and Iraola, surprises in Del Bosque's list|newspaper=Marca|language=Spanish|date=14 August 2011|accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> but did not leave the bench.\n\n===Venezuela===\nAs early as 2006, Amorebieta expressed his interest in playing for the [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela national team]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archivo.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/1a_division/athletic/es/desarrollo/720825.html|title=Fernando Amorebieta dispuesto a jugar ya con Venezuela|trans-title=Fernando Amorebieta willing to play for Venezuela immediately|newspaper=Marca|language=Spanish|date=19 December 2006|accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> However, according to [[FIFA]] rules at the time, he should have switched his affiliation prior to the age of 21, having previously played for Spain's youth sides.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archivo.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/1a_division/athletic/es/desarrollo/730290.html|title=Fernando Amorebieta no podr\u00e1 jugar con la selecci\u00f3n de Venezuela como quer\u00eda|trans-title=Fernando Amorebieta will not be able to play with Venezuela national team as he intended|newspaper=Marca|language=Spanish|date=19 January 2007|accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> FIFA removed the rule in 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=652502&cc=5739|title=Age limit on players switching nations is removed|publisher=[[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]]|date=4 June 2009|accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> and talks between the player and the [[Venezuelan Football Federation]] resumed.\n\nFinally, on 2 September 2011, Amorebieta made his senior debut in a friendly with [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], a 0\u20131 loss.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2011/09/02/futbol/equipos/athletic/1314981017.html|title=Amorebieta debuta con Venezuela|trans-title=Amorebieta makes Venezuela debut|newspaper=Marca|language=Spanish|date=2 September 2011|accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> On 11 October, against the same opponent but for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|qualifying campaign]], he scored in a 1\u20130 home win, which signified Venezuela's first-ever win against the ''Albiceleste'' in the tournament.<ref name=CAPITAL>{{cite news|url=http://www.lacapital.com.ar/ovacion/Gol-de-Amorebieta-y-Argentina-pierde-1-a-0-con-Venezuela--en-16-del-segundo-tiempo-20111011-0028.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121229230341/http://www.lacapital.com.ar/ovacion/Gol-de-Amorebieta-y-Argentina-pierde-1-a-0-con-Venezuela--en-16-del-segundo-tiempo-20111011-0028.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 December 2012|title=Venezuela hizo historia a costa de una desorientada y cansada Argentina|trans-title=Venezuela made history at the expense of dizzy and tired Argentina|newspaper=[[La Capital]]|language=Spanish|date=11 October 2011|accessdate=12 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nAmorebieta was included in Venezuela's squad for the [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica]], where he was sent off in the team's 0\u20131 loss to [[Peru national football team|Peru]] in the [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group C|group stage]] for a stamp on [[Paolo Guerrero]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/copa-america/match/409845/peru-venezuela/report|title=Claudio Pizarro goal pushes Peru past 10-man Venezuela|publisher=ESPN FC|date=18 June 2015|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref> He retired from international football that November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34975551|title=Venezuela: Salomon Rondon and squad in quit threat to board|publisher=BBC Sport|date=1 December 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Basque Country===\nAmorebieta also appeared in four matches for the [[Basque Country national football team|Basque Country national team]] (a non-FIFA affiliate), debuting against Venezuela in [[San Crist\u00f3bal, T\u00e1chira]] on 20 June 2007.<ref name=\"ATHLETIC\"/> The friendly match, a 4\u20133 Basque win, was the grand opening for the 43,000 all-seated [[Estadio Polideportivo de Pueblo Nuevo|Pueblo Nuevo Stadium]], after two years of construction for the [[2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.diariovasco.com/20070621/deportes/mas_futbol/euskadi-vencio-venezuela-goles_200706211011.html|title=Euskadi venci\u00f3 a Venezuela con goles de Gabilondo, Aduriz y Etxeberria|trans-title=Basque Country beat Venezuela with goals from Gabilondo, Aduriz and Etxeberria|newspaper=[[El Diario Vasco]]|language=Spanish|date=21 June 2007|accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|14 April 2020}}<ref>{{Athletic Bilbao profile|557|amorebieta|name=Amorebieta}}</ref><ref>{{ESPN FC|50453}}</ref><ref>{{Soccerway|3165|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Soccerbase|44854}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other<ref>Includes other competitive competitions, including the [[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]], [[UEFA Super Cup]], [[English Football League play-offs]], [[FIFA Club World Cup]].</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n|[[CD Basconia|Basconia]]\n|[[2003\u201304 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|2003\u201304]]\n|[[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]]\n|26||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||26||1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Bilbao Athletic]]\n|[[2004\u201305 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2004\u201305]]\n|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]\n|24||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||24||1\n|-\n|[[2005\u201306 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2005\u201306]]\n|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B\n|11||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||11||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!35!!1!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||35!!1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"9\"|[[Athletic Bilbao]]\n|[[2005\u201306 La Liga|2005\u201306]]\n|[[La Liga]]\n|15||0||2||0||2||0||0||0||19||0\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 La Liga|2006\u201307]]\n|La Liga\n|27||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||28||0\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 La Liga|2007\u201308]]\n|La Liga\n|34||0||6||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||40||1\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 La Liga|2008\u201309]]\n|La Liga\n|29||0||7||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||36||0\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 La Liga|2009\u201310]]\n|La Liga\n|34||0||2||0||11||0||0||0||47||0\n|-\n|[[201