{"title_page": "August Rauber", "text_new": "[[File:August Rauber.jpg|right|thumb|August Rauber (1841\u20131917)]]\n'''August Rauber''' (March 9, 1841 &ndash; February 16, 1917) was a German [[anatomist]] and [[embryologist]] born in [[Obermoschel]] in the [[Rhineland-Palatinate]].\n\nRauber was born the fourth of five children to Stephan Rauber and Rosalie n\u00e9e Oberl\u00e9.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 1605361 | volume=174 | title=August Rauber | date=February 1992 | journal=Ann. Anat. | pages=6\u201310  | last1 = Kogerman-Lepp | first1 = E}}</ref> He studied medicine in [[University of Munich|Munich]], obtaining his doctorate in 1865. At Munich his instructors included [[Theodor Ludwig Wilhelm Bischoff|Theodor Bischoff]] (1807\u20131882), [[Nicolaus R\u00fcdinger]] (1832\u20131896) and [[Julius Kollmann]] (1834\u20131918).<ref name=LE>[http://drw.saw-leipzig.de/30838.html Drw.saw-leipzig.de] (biography)</ref>\n\nIn 1869 he obtained his habilitation, and in 1872 worked as a dissector at the [[University of Basel]]. Shortly afterwards, he relocated to the [[University of Leipzig]], where he worked under [[Wilhelm His, Sr.|Wilhelm His]] (1831\u20131904). From 1873 to 1886 he was an associate professor of anatomy and [[anthropology]] at Leipzig.<ref name=LE/>\n\nIn 1886, he became a professor of anatomy and head of the anatomical institute at the [[University of Tartu|University of Dorpat]].<ref name=LE/> He worked as a professor in [[Tartu]] (Dorpat) for 25 years and also started the anatomy collection of the University of Tartu.\n\nIn his studies involving the [[embryonic development]] of birds and mammals, Rauber is credited with combining comparative [[embryology]] and [[histology]] with [[phylogenetic]] analysis.<ref>{{cite journal |pages=439\u201349 |doi=10.1387/ijdb.052127sb |title=August Rauber (1841-1917): From the primitive streak to Cellularmechanik |year=2006 |last1=Brauckmann |first1=Sabine |journal=The International Journal of Developmental Biology |volume=50 |pmid=16586344 |issue=5|url=http://www.ijdb.ehu.es/web/descarga/paper/052127sb |doi-access=free }}</ref> The eponymous \"Rauber's layer\" bears his name, being defined as a [[trophoblast]]ic membrane over the [[embryonic disk]] in developing animals.<ref>[http://www.mondofacto.com/facts/dictionary?Rauber's+layer Mondofacto Dictionary] Definition of eponym</ref>\n\nHe is buried to the [[Uus-Jaani cemetery]] in Tartu.\n\n== Partial list of publications ==\n* ''Vater'sche K\u00f6rperchen der B\u00e4nder- und Periostnerven und ihre Beziehung zum sog. Muskelsinne'' (1865).\n* ''Untersuchungen \u00fcber das Vorkommen und die Bedeutung der Vaterschen K\u00f6rperchen'' (1867).\n* ''Elasticit\u00e4t und Festigkeit der Knochen'', 1876 - Elasticity and strength of bones.\n* ''\u00dcber den Ursprung der Milch und die Ern\u00e4hrung der Frucht im Allgemeinen'' (1879).\n* ''Urgeschichte der Menschen'', (two volumes) 1884 - Prehistory of man.\n* ''Homo sapiens ferus'' (1885) - [[Homo sapiens]] ferus.\n* ''Oder die Zust\u00e4nde der Verwilderten und ihre Bedeutung f\u00fcr Wissenschaft, Politik und Schule (1885).\n* ''\u00dcber die Bedeutung der wissenschaftlichen Anatomie'', 1886 - On the importance of scientific anatomy.\n* ''Atlas der Krystallregeneration'' (four volumes), 1896/97 - Atlas of \"crystal regeneration\".\n* ''Die Aufgaben des Lebens'' (1896).\n* ''Lehrbuch der Anatomie des Menschen'' (two volumes) - Textbook of [[human anatomy]] - (5th edition 1897/98), continued by [[Friedrich Wilhelm Kopsch]] (1868-1955).<ref>[https://openlibrary.org/books/OL24970545M/Rauber's_Lehrbuch_der_Anatomie_des_Menschen Open Library] Rauber's Lehrbuch der Anatomie des Menschen</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=H5UTAQAAMAAJ Google Books] Rauber-Kopsch Lehrbuch und Atlas der Anatomie des Menschen: Eingewiede Nervensystem Sinnersorgane</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=August Rauber}}\n* [http://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?hl=en&sl=de&u=http://www.zeno.org/Pagel-1901/A/Rauber,%2BAugust&prev=/search%3Fq%3D%2522Rauber,%2BAugust%2522%2BPagel%26start%3D10%26hl%3Den%26sa%3DN%26rlz%3D1R2GGLL_en&rurl=translate.google.com&usg=ALkJrhiI9jipfFUP-RbyrPnXcwZb8SPcyA Translated biography and list of publications] @ Pagel: Biographical Encyclopedia\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rauber, August}}\n[[Category:1841 births]]\n[[Category:1917 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Donnersbergkreis]]\n[[Category:German anatomists]]\n[[Category:Embryologists]]\n[[Category:University of Tartu faculty]]\n[[Category:Leipzig University faculty]]\n[[Category:People from the Palatinate (region)]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:August Rauber.jpg|right|thumb|August Rauber (1841\u20131917)]]\n'''August Rauber''' (March 9, 1841 &ndash; February 16, 1917) was a German [[anatomist]] and [[embryologist]] born in [[Obermoschel]] in the [[Rhineland-Palatinate]].\n\nRauber was born the fourth of five children to Stephan Rauber and Rosalie n\u00e9e Oberl\u00e9.<ref>E Kogerman-Lepp. August Rauber. \u201eAnnals of Anatomy - Anatomischer Anzeiger\u201d. 174 (1), s. 6-10, 1992. doi:10.1016/S0940-9602(11)80333-X. {{PMID|1605361}}.</ref> He studied medicine in [[University of Munich|Munich]], obtaining his doctorate in 1865. At Munich his instructors included [[Theodor Ludwig Wilhelm Bischoff|Theodor Bischoff]] (1807\u20131882), [[Nicolaus R\u00fcdinger]] (1832\u20131896) and [[Julius Kollmann]] (1834\u20131918).<ref name=LE>[http://drw.saw-leipzig.de/30838.html Drw.saw-leipzig.de] (biography)</ref>\n\nIn 1869 he obtained his habilitation, and in 1872 worked as a dissector at the [[University of Basel]]. Shortly afterwards, he relocated to the [[University of Leipzig]], where he worked under [[Wilhelm His, Sr.|Wilhelm His]] (1831\u20131904). From 1873 to 1886 he was an associate professor of anatomy and [[anthropology]] at Leipzig.<ref name=LE/>\n\nIn 1886, he became a professor of anatomy and head of the anatomical institute at the [[University of Tartu|University of Dorpat]].<ref name=LE/> He worked as a professor in [[Tartu]] (Dorpat) for 25 years and also started the anatomy collection of the University of Tartu.\n\nIn his studies involving the [[embryonic development]] of birds and mammals, Rauber is credited with combining comparative [[embryology]] and [[histology]] with [[phylogenetic]] analysis.<ref>{{cite journal |pages=439\u201349 |doi=10.1387/ijdb.052127sb |title=August Rauber (1841-1917): From the primitive streak to Cellularmechanik |year=2006 |last1=Brauckmann |first1=Sabine |journal=The International Journal of Developmental Biology |volume=50 |pmid=16586344 |issue=5|url=http://www.ijdb.ehu.es/web/descarga/paper/052127sb |doi-access=free }}</ref> The eponymous \"Rauber's layer\" bears his name, being defined as a [[trophoblast]]ic membrane over the [[embryonic disk]] in developing animals.<ref>[http://www.mondofacto.com/facts/dictionary?Rauber's+layer Mondofacto Dictionary] Definition of eponym</ref>\n\nHe is buried to the [[Uus-Jaani cemetery]] in Tartu.\n\n== Partial list of publications ==\n* ''Vater'sche K\u00f6rperchen der B\u00e4nder- und Periostnerven und ihre Beziehung zum sog. Muskelsinne'' (1865).\n* ''Untersuchungen \u00fcber das Vorkommen und die Bedeutung der Vaterschen K\u00f6rperchen'' (1867).\n* ''Elasticit\u00e4t und Festigkeit der Knochen'', 1876 - Elasticity and strength of bones.\n* ''\u00dcber den Ursprung der Milch und die Ern\u00e4hrung der Frucht im Allgemeinen'' (1879).\n* ''Urgeschichte der Menschen'', (two volumes) 1884 - Prehistory of man.\n* ''Homo sapiens ferus'' (1885) - [[Homo sapiens]] ferus.\n* ''Oder die Zust\u00e4nde der Verwilderten und ihre Bedeutung f\u00fcr Wissenschaft, Politik und Schule (1885).\n* ''\u00dcber die Bedeutung der wissenschaftlichen Anatomie'', 1886 - On the importance of scientific anatomy.\n* ''Atlas der Krystallregeneration'' (four volumes), 1896/97 - Atlas of \"crystal regeneration\".\n* ''Die Aufgaben des Lebens'' (1896).\n* ''Lehrbuch der Anatomie des Menschen'' (two volumes) - Textbook of [[human anatomy]] - (5th edition 1897/98), continued by [[Friedrich Wilhelm Kopsch]] (1868-1955).<ref>[https://openlibrary.org/books/OL24970545M/Rauber's_Lehrbuch_der_Anatomie_des_Menschen Open Library] Rauber's Lehrbuch der Anatomie des Menschen</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=H5UTAQAAMAAJ Google Books] Rauber-Kopsch Lehrbuch und Atlas der Anatomie des Menschen: Eingewiede Nervensystem Sinnersorgane</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=August Rauber}}\n* [http://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?hl=en&sl=de&u=http://www.zeno.org/Pagel-1901/A/Rauber,%2BAugust&prev=/search%3Fq%3D%2522Rauber,%2BAugust%2522%2BPagel%26start%3D10%26hl%3Den%26sa%3DN%26rlz%3D1R2GGLL_en&rurl=translate.google.com&usg=ALkJrhiI9jipfFUP-RbyrPnXcwZb8SPcyA Translated biography and list of publications] @ Pagel: Biographical Encyclopedia\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rauber, August}}\n[[Category:1841 births]]\n[[Category:1917 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Donnersbergkreis]]\n[[Category:German anatomists]]\n[[Category:Embryologists]]\n[[Category:University of Tartu faculty]]\n[[Category:Leipzig University faculty]]\n[[Category:People from the Palatinate (region)]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/August_Rauber"}
{"title_page": "Karol Olgierd Borchardt", "text_new": "[[File:Karol Olgierd Borchardt.jpg|thumb|Karol Olgierd Borchardt]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2011}}\n'''Karol Olgierd Borchardt''' (25 March 1905 \u2013 20 May 1986) was a [[Poland|Polish]] writer and [[Captain (nautical)|captain]] of the [[Polish Merchant Marine]].               \n\n== Biography ==\nBorn to Polish parents of German blood descent in Moscow, he spent the vast majority of his life and died in [[Gdynia]]. Borchardt gained a place in history of the Polish Merchant Marine as an officer on Polish transatlantic liners and training sail ships. During the [[World War II]] he served i/a on two  Polish liners converted into troop transports (the m/v PI\u0142SUDSKI and the m/v CHROBRY), and survived the loss of both. After the war he trained two generations of Polish officers. While demanding, he was also a warm-hearted and understanding teacher and an excellent lecturer. He also became famous as the writer and chronicler of i/a Polish passenger liners.\n\n== Works ==\nHis books are tribute to his captains \u2013 [[Mamert Stankiewicz]] and Eustazy Borkowski, and they are valuable additions to the record of Polish maritime history. Along with two volumes dedicated to two of his captains, he also wrote a book on two 'cradles' of Polish seadogs, the two sail-training vessels, \"Lw\u00f3w\" and the \"Dar Pomorza\". There are many schools named after him, which is an irrefutable proof that Karol Olgierd Borchardt is still remembered as a hero of [[Gdynia]].\nHe was extremely strong-willed, set goals for himself on a regular basis and, what is more, he was open-minded, caring and inquiring as well. His book ''Znaczy kapitan'' describes fascinating adventures at sea in a humorous and informative way, mostly connected with [[Mamert Stankiewicz]]. The book ''Szaman morski'' tells the tales about Eustazy Borkowski. The title is a nickname of this extraordinary sea captain (eng. sea shaman). The titles of his books are very difficult to translate into English.\nKarol Olgierd Borchardt was a very tall and strong man. Moreover, even in his elderly years, he still continued practicing  sports.\n\n*Achievements\n**Books: Znaczy kapitan (1960), Kr\u0105\u017cownik spod Somosierry (1963), Szaman Morski (1968)\n**[[Cross of Valor (Poland)|Cross of Valour]] (1920 and 1941)\n**[[Cross of Merit (Poland)|Cross of Merit]] (1957)\n** Medal of Ministry of National Education of the Republic of Poland (1970)\n**Gdynia's President Prize (1974)\n* The \"Kapitan Borchardt\", a Polish sail training three-masted gaff schooner, in service since 2011, is named after Karol Olgierd Borchardt.\n\n==References==\n{{Unreferenced|date=February 2007}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.kapitanborchardt.pl/ Website] of the eponymous schooner\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Borchardt, Karol}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:Polish male writers]]\n[[Category:Polish people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Cross of Valour (Poland)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Cross of Merit (Poland)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2011}}\n'''Karol Olgierd Borchardt''' (25 March 1905 \u2013 20 May 1986) was a [[Poland|Polish]] writer and [[Captain (nautical)|captain]] of the [[Polish Merchant Marine]].\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn to Polish parents of German blood descent in Moscow, he spent the vast majority of his life and died in [[Gdynia]]. Borchardt gained a place in history of the Polish Merchant Marine as an officer on Polish transatlantic liners and training sail ships. During the [[World War II]] he served i/a on two  Polish liners converted into troop transports (the m/v PI\u0142SUDSKI and the m/v CHROBRY), and survived the loss of both. After the war he trained two generations of Polish officers. While demanding, he was also a warm-hearted and understanding teacher and an excellent lecturer. He also became famous as the writer and chronicler of i/a Polish passenger liners.\n\n== Works ==\nHis books are tribute to his captains \u2013 [[Mamert Stankiewicz]] and Eustazy Borkowski, and they are valuable additions to the record of Polish maritime history. Along with two volumes dedicated to two of his captains, he also wrote a book on two 'cradles' of Polish seadogs, the two sail-training vessels, \"Lw\u00f3w\" and the \"Dar Pomorza\". There are many schools named after him, which is an irrefutable proof that Karol Olgierd Borchardt is still remembered as a hero of [[Gdynia]].\nHe was extremely strong-willed, set goals for himself on a regular basis and, what is more, he was open-minded, caring and inquiring as well. His book ''Znaczy kapitan'' describes fascinating adventures at sea in a humorous and informative way, mostly connected with [[Mamert Stankiewicz]]. The book ''Szaman morski'' tells the tales about Eustazy Borkowski. The title is a nickname of this extraordinary sea captain (eng. sea shaman). The titles of his books are very difficult to translate into English.\nKarol Olgierd Borchardt was a very tall and strong man. Moreover, even in his elderly years, he still continued practicing  sports.\n\n*Achievements\n**Books: Znaczy kapitan (1960), Kr\u0105\u017cownik spod Somosierry (1963), Szaman Morski (1968)\n**[[Cross of Valor (Poland)|Cross of Valour]] (1920 and 1941)\n**[[Cross of Merit (Poland)|Cross of Merit]] (1957)\n** Medal of Ministry of National Education of the Republic of Poland (1970)\n**Gdynia's President Prize (1974)\n* The \"Kapitan Borchardt\", a Polish sail training three-masted gaff schooner, in service since 2011, is named after Karol Olgierd Borchardt.\n\n==References==\n{{Unreferenced|date=February 2007}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.kapitanborchardt.pl/ Website] of the eponymous schooner\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Borchardt, Karol}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:Polish male writers]]\n[[Category:Polish people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Cross of Valour (Poland)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Cross of Merit (Poland)]]\n", "name_user": "Wiktor Nowicki", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karol_Olgierd_Borchardt"}
